{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{Use British English|date=February 2015}} {{about| architectural foils|other types of foil|Foil (disambiguation)}} A '''foil''' is an architectural device based on a symmetrical rendering of leaf shapes, defined by overlapping circles that produce a series of cusps to make a lobe. Typically, the number of cusps can be three (''[[trefoil]]''), four (''[[quatrefoil]]'') or five (''cinquefoil''<ref>[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/cinquefoil Cinquefoil – Wiktionary]</ref>), or can be any number (''multifoil'').<ref name=Pevsner>[[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner, Nikolaus]]; [[John Harris (curator)|Harris, John]]: ''The Buildings of England: Lincolnshire'', Penguin (1964); revised by Nicholas Antram (1989), [[Yale University Press]], p.&nbsp;726. {{ISBN|0300096208}}</ref> Foil motifs may be used as part of the heads and [[tracery]] of [[Window#Terms|window lights]], complete windows themselves, the underside of arches, in [[heraldry]], within panelling, and as part of any decorative or ornament device. Foil types are commonly found in [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] and [[Islamic architecture|Islamic]] architecture. <gallery caption="Foil Type Examples" widths="180" heights="120" perrow="6"> File:Trefoil-Architectural.svg|Trefoil File:Quatrefoil-Architectural.svg|Quatrefoil File:Chambers 1908 Cinquefoil.png|Cinquefoil File:Champagne-sur-Oise Notre-Dame-de-l’Assomption Triumphbogen 195.JPG|Multifoil (eighteen) File:Aljaferia - Portique nord.JPG|[[Aljafería]], Zaragoza, Spain </gallery>
